    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That sounds pretty risky. Does this clause allow them to come after my personal assets, like my car or savings, if the business side of things doesn't cover it? Is there any way to limit this kind of exposure in the contract?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, you're venturing into the murky waters of personal liability, where the waters can indeed get murky. The indemnification clause can potentially lead to situations where the Client might seek compensation beyond the business assets, which could, in some cases, include your personal assets. It's like a dragon guarding a treasure hoard; if the treasure isn't enough, the dragon might come after your belongings.\n\nTo limit this kind of exposure, you can negotiate terms within the contract. For instance, you could try to include a cap on the amount you're responsible for, or specify that the indemnification only applies to business assets, not personal ones. It's like putting up a moat around your castle; you want to make sure that the dragon can't just come after your personal treasures. However, it's important to note that negotiating these terms can be a delicate dance, and the Client might not always agree to your proposals. It's always wise to consult with a legal professional who can help you navigate these treacherous waters and ensure that your interests are well-protected.",
      "source": "target",
